Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: Principles of Phonetics
Details: Understand and be able to describe the general principles of phonetics, e.g., what the difference is between stops, fricatives, nasals, how voicing is produced, the parts of the articulatory tract, etc.;

Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: German Phonetic and Phonemic Systems
Details: be able to describe the German phonetic and phonemic system and how it differs from the native language (i.e., English) and be able to provide the names of each of the sounds in both English and German;

Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: Pronunciation Refinement
Details: have eliminated phonemic errors (wrong sounds) and further refined their own pronunciation (reducing or eliminating foreign accent);

Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: International Phonetic Alphabet
Details: be able to use IPA (International Phonetic Alphabet) to transcribe the German language;

Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: Articulation of German Phonemes and Allophones
Details: be able to describe the articulation of the German phonemes and allophones;

Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: Evaluating and Improving Pronunciation
Details: be able to employ the tools learned in class to both evaluate and improve their own pronunciation of German as well as the pronunciation of others (including but not limited to articulatory explanations, rudimentary acoustic analysis, etc.);

Analyze the following learning outcome and provide confidence scores for how well it aligns with each BYU Aim:

Title: Improving General Proficiency
Details: have taken the opportunity to improve their general proficiency, including grammar, vocabulary, cultural knowledge and functional ability;
